---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import CTADementia from "../../components/CTADementia.astro";
import ContactForm from "../../components/ContactForm.astro";
import Header from "../../components/Header.astro";

const landingData = {
  partners: {
    id: "partners",
    heading: "Need help?",
    description:
      "If you or a loved one in the Sarasota-Bradenton area is facing the challenges of dementia, help is available at Right Accord Home Health Care as well as Right Accord Placement Services. Our compassionate team provides personalized in-home care designed to support families and individuals struggling with dementia. Whether you need assistance with daily activities, memory care, or emotional support, we are here to help. Contact us today to learn how we can improve quality of life for you and your family.",
    logos: [
      {
        imagePath: "/src/assets/holding-hands-with-senior-patient.jpg",
        imageAlt: "holding hands with senior patient",
      },
    ],
  },
  header: {
    imagePath: "/src/assets/care-provider-posing-for-picture-with-senior-patient.jpg",
    imageAlt: "care provider posing for picture with senior patient",
    headerH1: "Alzheimer's Disease",
    paragraph: "Alzheimer’s disease is a progressive neurological disorder affecting memory, thinking, and behavior. It is the most common cause of dementia, leading to cognitive decline and an increasing need for care.",
    buttons: [
      {
        name: "Contact",
        link: "#contact-us"
      },
      {
        name: "Need Assistance?",
        link: "#help"
      },
    ]
  }
};
---

<BaseLayout
  siteTitle="Understanding Alzheimer's Disease | Causes, Symptoms & Care Options" 
  siteDescription="Learn about Alzheimer's disease, its causes, early symptoms, and how it progresses over time. Discover treatment options, caregiving strategies, and resources for families navigating this condition." 
  keywords="Alzheimer’s disease, memory loss, dementia symptoms, cognitive decline, brain health, early signs of Alzheimer’s, Alzheimer’s treatment, dementia care, senior care, neurological disorders, Alzheimer's stages, caregiving for Alzheimer's, memory care"
>
  <Header data={landingData.header} />
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-purple-900 mb-6">Alzheimer’s Disease: Understanding the Condition, Symptoms, and Care</h1>

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <section class="mb-8">
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">
            Alzheimer’s disease is a progressive neurological disorder affecting memory, thinking, and behavior. It is the most common cause of dementia, leading to cognitive decline and an increasing need for care.
        </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Symptoms -->
    <section class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-4">Symptoms and Early Warning Signs</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-lg text-gray-700 space-y-2">
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Memory Loss:</span> Forgetting recent conversations, names, or events.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Confusion with Time and Place:</span> Losing track of dates or locations.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Difficulty with Problem-Solving:</span> Struggling with finances or following a recipe.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Mood and Personality Changes:</span> Increased anxiety, depression, or social withdrawal.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Trouble Finding Words:</span> Difficulty speaking or writing.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Poor Judgment:</span> Making unusual decisions, such as mismanaging money.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Causes -->
    <section class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-4">Causes and Risk Factors</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">While the exact cause is unknown, several factors contribute to Alzheimer’s disease:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-lg text-gray-700 space-y-2 mt-2">
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Age:</span> Risk increases significantly after age 65.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Genetics:</span> Family history and genes like APOE-e4 raise the risk.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Heart Health:</span> Conditions like diabetes, high blood pressure, and obesity may contribute.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Brain Changes:</span> Protein deposits (amyloid plaques, tau tangles) disrupt brain function.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Stages -->
    <section class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-4">Stages of Alzheimer’s Disease</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-white p-4 shadow-md rounded-lg">
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800">Mild (Early Stage)</h3>
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">Memory lapses, difficulty with tasks, and subtle personality changes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white p-4 shadow-md rounded-lg">
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800">Moderate (Middle Stage)</h3>
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">Increased confusion, difficulty recognizing loved ones, and behavioral changes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white p-4 shadow-md rounded-lg">
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800">Severe (Late Stage)</h3>
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">Significant memory loss, loss of mobility, and the need for full-time care.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Treatment -->
    <section class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-4">Treatment and Management</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">
            While there is no cure, treatments help manage symptoms:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-lg text-gray-700 space-y-2 mt-2">
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Medications:</span> Cholinesterase inhibitors (donepezil, rivastigmine) may slow decline.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Lifestyle Changes:</span> Exercise, brain-healthy diets, and mental stimulation help.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Supportive Care:</span> Structured routines and caregiver assistance improve quality of life.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Caregiving -->
    <section class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-4">Caring for a Loved One</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">Caregivers play a crucial role. Some essential tips include:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-lg text-gray-700 space-y-2 mt-2">
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Creating a Safe Environment:</span> Reduce fall risks and use reminders.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Encouraging Independence:</span> Allow tasks they can still manage.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Communication Strategies:</span> Use simple phrases and reassurance.</li>
            <li><span class="font-semibold">Seeking Support:</span> Support groups and respite care can help caregivers.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Future Research -->
    <section class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-4">Hope for the Future</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">
            Research is ongoing, with new treatments, early detection methods, and potential cures in development. Clinical trials offer hope for managing Alzheimer’s more effectively.
        </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <CTADementia data={landingData.partners} />
  <ContactForm />
</BaseLayout>
